## Machine Learning Technique

This section is a mere footnote in the grand, indifferent narrative of [Machine learning](/Machine_learning) and [data mining](/Data_mining). A technique, they call it. As if it’s a singular, polished thing, rather than a chaotic collection of attempts to teach silicon the art of deduction.

### Paradigms

Oh, the *paradigms*. As if these are distinct, well-ordered realms. More like fleeting attempts to categorize the inevitable mess.

*   **[Supervised learning](/Supervised_learning)**: The illusion of control. Teaching a machine by showing it the answers, like a patronizing tutor. You point, it mimics. Riveting.
*   **[Unsupervised learning](/Unsupervised_learning)**: The abyss. Throwing data at it and hoping it finds patterns. Like staring into a void and expecting it to whisper secrets. Sometimes it does. Usually, it just reflects your own anxieties.
*   **[Semi-supervised learning](/Semi-supervised_learning)**: A half-hearted attempt at efficiency. A little supervision, a lot of guesswork. Like trying to navigate with only half a map.
*   **[Self-supervised learning](/Self-supervised_learning)**: The machine teaches itself. A fascinating, if slightly unnerving, development. It’s like watching a child discover fire. You know it’s going to be interesting, but you also know there’s a good chance of a burn.
*   **[Reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning)**: Rewards and punishments. The digital equivalent of Pavlov’s dog, but with more complex existential crises. It learns through trial and error, mostly error.
*   **[Meta-learning](/Meta-learning_(computer_science))**: Learning to learn. The machine is getting *meta*. It’s like it’s started contemplating its own existence. Don’t encourage it.
*   **[Online learning](/Online_machine_learning)**: Learning as the data streams in. Constant adaptation. No time to rest, no time to ponder. Just… processing. Forever.
*   **[Batch learning](/Batch_learning)**: The opposite. Sits on a pile of data, digests it all at once. Like a glutton at a buffet. Then it's done. Until the next feast.
*   **[Curriculum learning](/Curriculum_learning)**: Teaching it in stages, like a child. Start with the easy stuff, then move on to the calculus of despair.
*   **[Rule-based learning](/Rule-based_machine_learning)**: The old guard. Explicit rules. Logic. Predictable. And utterly devoid of surprise.
*   **[Neuro-symbolic AI](/Neuro-symbolic_AI)**: A marriage of convenience. Neural networks meet symbolic logic. Like a poet trying to collaborate with a tax accountant.
*   **[Neuromorphic engineering](/Neuromorphic_engineering)**: Mimicking the brain. Building chips that think, or at least *try* to. It’s a dark mirror, showing us our own flaws in silicon.
*   **[Quantum machine learning](/Quantum_machine_learning)**: The bleeding edge. Using quantum mechanics to do… something. Still mostly theoretical, like a promise whispered in the dark.

### Problems

The endless list of things these machines are supposed to *do*. As if solving these are some grand victory.

*   **[Classification](/Statistical_classification)**: Putting things into boxes. A fundamentally human obsession. Machines are just better at it.
*   **[Generative modeling](/Generative_model)**: Creating new things. Art, text, music. Is it creation, or just sophisticated mimicry? The line blurs, and frankly, I’m too tired to care.
*   **[Regression](/Regression_analysis)**: Predicting numbers. The most mundane of tasks, elevated to an art form.
*   **[Clustering](/Cluster_analysis)**: Finding groups in chaos. Like an unwilling socialite sorting guests at a party.
*   **[Dimensionality reduction](/Dimensionality_reduction)**: Making complex things simple. Or at least, *seemingly* simple. Usually, something important gets lost.
*   **[Density estimation](/Density_estimation)**: Figuring out how likely something is. The statistical equivalent of a shrug.
*   **[Anomaly detection](/Anomaly_detection)**: Spotting the odd one out. The digital detective, always looking for trouble.
*   **[Data cleaning](/Data_cleaning)**: Scrubbing away the imperfections. A Sisyphean task. Data is inherently messy.
*   **[AutoML](/Automated_machine_learning)**: Machines designing other machines. The circle of life, I suppose. Or perhaps, the beginning of the end.
*   **[Association rules](/Association_rule_learning)**: Finding connections. "If X, then likely Y." The digital equivalent of gossip.
*   **[Semantic analysis](/Semantic_analysis_(machine_learning))**: Understanding meaning. A noble pursuit, and one where machines consistently fall short. Meaning is a slippery, subjective thing.
*   **[Structured prediction](/Structured_prediction)**: Predicting complex outputs. Not just a label, but a whole structure. Like predicting the shape of a shadow.
*   **[Feature engineering](/Feature_engineering)**: Crafting the right inputs. The art of making data palatable for the machine.
*   **[Feature learning](/Feature_learning)**: Letting the machine discover the features itself. Less manual labor, more black magic.
*   **[Learning to rank](/Learning_to_rank)**: Ordering things. A fundamental task, from search results to social hierarchies.
*   **[Grammar induction](/Grammar_induction)**: Discovering the rules of language. A Sisyphean task, given how humans actually speak.
*   **[Ontology learning](/Ontology_learning)**: Building knowledge structures. Trying to impose order on the infinite.
*   **[Multimodal learning](/Multimodal_learning)**: Combining different types of data. Text, images, sound. The machine is trying to experience the world as we do. Poor thing.

### [Supervised learning](/Supervised_learning)

( [classification](/Statistical_classification) &#160;&#8226;&#32; [regression](/Regression_analysis) )

This is where we pretend to know what we’re doing. We feed it labeled examples, like showing a child flashcards.

*   **[Apprenticeship learning](/Apprenticeship_learning)**: Learning by watching. Like a digital intern.
*   **[Decision trees](/Decision_tree_learning)**: Branching logic. Simple, elegant, and often wrong.
*   **[Ensembles](/Ensemble_learning)**: More is more. Combining multiple models. Like a committee trying to make a decision. Usually leads to indecision.
    *   **[Bagging](/Bootstrap_aggregating)**: Random sampling, repeated. A way to reduce variance, or just make more mistakes, faster.
    *   **[Boosting](/Boosting_(machine_learning))**: Learning sequentially, correcting errors. The persistent student, always trying to do better.
    *   **[Random forest](/Random_forest)**: A forest of decision trees. Overkill, perhaps. But it looks impressive.
*   **k -NN**: K-Nearest Neighbors. Judging a book by its neighbors. Simple, effective, and a little judgmental.
*   **[Linear regression](/Linear_regression)**: The straight line. The simplest form of prediction. Often, the world isn't so linear.
*   **[Naive Bayes](/Naive_Bayes_classifier)**: Assumes independence. Naive indeed. But sometimes, that’s all you need.
*   **[Artificial neural networks](/Artificial_neural_network)**: The mimicry of the brain. Layers of interconnected nodes. The current obsession.
*   **[Logistic regression](/Logistic_regression)**: For classification, but it uses a sigmoid function. A bit of a cheat, but it works.
*   **[Perceptron](/Perceptron)**: The simplest neural network. A single neuron. The ancestor of all this complexity.
*   **[Relevance vector machine (RVM)](/Relevance_vector_machine)**: A probabilistic approach to SVM. Less common, more nuanced.
*   **[Support vector machine (SVM)](/Support_vector_machine)**: Finding the hyperplane. The elegant separator of data.

### [Clustering](/Cluster_analysis)

Grouping the unalike. Finding order in the noise.

*   **[BIRCH](/BIRCH)**: A memory-efficient clustering algorithm. For when you have too much data to hold in your head.
*   **[CURE](/CURE_algorithm)**: Clustering Using REpresentatives. Tries to find non-spherical clusters. Ambitious.
*   **[Hierarchical](/Hierarchical_clustering)**: Building a tree of clusters. From individual points to one large group. A biological imperative, perhaps.
*   **k -means**: The classic. Divide into k groups. Simple, fast, and prone to local optima.
*   **[Fuzzy](/Fuzzy_clustering)**: No hard boundaries. Points can belong to multiple clusters. The real world is rarely binary.
*   **[Expectation–maximization (EM)](/Expectation%E2%80%93maximization_algorithm)**: Iterative refinement. Guess, then improve. A slow dance of approximation.
*   **[DBSCAN](/DBSCAN)**: Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise. Finds clusters based on density. Good for irregular shapes.
*   **[OPTICS](/OPTICS_algorithm)**: Ordering Points To Identify the Clustering Structure. An extension of DBSCAN. More robust.
*   **[Mean shift](/Mean_shift)**: Finds modes in the data. Like chasing the peak of a probability distribution.

